# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: hydro-one
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:hydro-one/2018-ontario-election-p01] General elections were held on June 7, 2018, to elect the 124 members of the 42nd Parliament of Ontario.
[src:hydro-one/2018-ontario-election-p01] The Progressive Conservative Party of Ontario, led by Doug Ford, won 76 of the 124 seats in the legislature and formed a majority government.
[src:hydro-one/2018-ontario-election-p01] The Ontario New Democratic Party, led by Andrea Horwath, formed the Official Opposition.
[src:hydro-one/2018-ontario-election-p01] The Ontario Liberal Party, led by incumbent Premier Kathleen Wynne, lost official party status in recording both the worst result in the party's 161-year history and the worst result for any incumbent governing party in Ontario.
[src:hydro-one/2018-ontario-election-p01] The Green Party of Ontario won a seat for the first time in their history, while the Trillium Party of Ontario lost its single seat gained by a floor-crossing during the 41st Parliament.
[src:hydro-one/2018-ontario-election-p01] The *Electoral Boundaries Act, 2015* increased the number of electoral districts from 107 to 122, following the boundaries set out by the federal 2013 Representation Order for Ontario, while preserving the special boundaries of the 11 seats in Northern Ontario set out in the 1996 redistribution.
[src:hydro-one/2018-ontario-election-p01] The Far North Electoral Boundaries Commission, appointed in 2016, recommended the creation of the additional districts of Kiiwetinoong and Mushkegowuk—James Bay, carved out from the existing Kenora—Rainy River and Timmins—James Bay ridings, which accordingly raised the total number of seats to 124.
[src:hydro-one/2018-ontario-election-p01] This was implemented through the *Representation Statute Law Amendment Act, 2017*.
[src:hydro-one/2018-ontario-election-p01] The new districts have been criticized as undemocratic, as they have a population of around 30,000 people compared with over 120,000 people in some southern Ontario constituencies.
[src:hydro-one/2018-ontario-election-p01] *National Post* columnist Josh Dehaas suggested that the small population sizes of the ridings might violate the Canadian Charter of Rights and Freedoms.
[src:hydro-one/2018-ontario-election-p01] In September 2017, a research firm analyzed the impact of redistribution if the boundaries had been in effect for the previous election.
[src:hydro-one/2018-ontario-election-p01] Under legislation passed in 2005, Ontario elections were to be held on "the first Thursday in October in the fourth calendar year following polling day in the most recent general election", subject to the Lieutenant-Governor of Ontario's power to call an election earlier.
[src:hydro-one/2018-ontario-election-p01] The Ontario Liberal Party attempted to win their fifth consecutive general election, dating back to 2003.
[src:hydro-one/2018-ontario-election-p01] The Progressive Conservative Party of Ontario won their first election since 1999, and the Ontario New Democratic Party attempted to win their second election (having previously won in 1990).
[src:hydro-one/2018-ontario-election-p01] Numerous other extra-parliamentary political parties also vied for votes.
[src:hydro-one/2018-ontario-election-p01] The Liberals under Kathleen Wynne headed into the 2018 campaign trailing far behind the Progressive Conservatives, led by former Toronto City Councillor Doug Ford.
[src:hydro-one/2018-ontario-election-p01] The Liberals' standing with voters had been badly hurt when they partially privatized Hydro One in 2015, after campaigning against it in the 2014 election, as well as rising criticism over "ballooning provincial debt, high electricity prices and costly, politically expedient decisions".
[src:hydro-one/2018-ontario-election-p01] PC leader Doug Ford called the budget a "spending spree".
[src:hydro-one/2018-ontario-election-p01] According to *Toronto Star* columnist Susan Delacourt, voters were motivated by a desire for change—such desire being more driven by emotion than by ideology—and one researcher estimated that more than half of the electorate was undecided in who they were likely to vote for.
[src:hydro-one/2018-ontario-election-p01] The *Huffington Post* reported that half of voters were basing their vote intentions on how best to block the party they oppose.
[src:hydro-one/2018-ontario-election-p01] In February 2018, the PC leadership overturned the nomination of candidates Karma Macgregor in Ottawa West—Nepean and Thenusha Parani in Scarborough Centre because of irregularities and allegations of ballot stuffing at their nomination meetings.
[src:hydro-one/2018-ontario-election-p01] The nomination meetings were reorganized, and both candidates lost the nomination at those meetings.
[src:hydro-one/2018-ontario-election-p01] However, the PC leadership decided not to overturn the nomination meeting's result in Hamilton West—Ancaster—Dundas, where a similar situation took place, because of an ongoing police investigation on this situation.
[src:hydro-one/2018-ontario-election-p01] In March 2018, the NDP nominated Lyra Evans as their candidate in Ottawa—Vanier.
[src:hydro-one/2018-ontario-election-p01] Evans was the first openly transgender candidate nominated by a major party to run in an Ontario general election.
[src:hydro-one/2018-ontario-election-p02] Elections Ontario used electronic vote tabulator machines from Dominion Voting Systems for counting the ballots.
[src:hydro-one/2018-ontario-election-p02] Tabulators were deployed at 50 per cent of polling stations at a cost of CA$32,000,000.
[src:hydro-one/2018-ontario-election-p02] This election was the first time Ontario used vote counting machines for a provincial election, although tabulators have been used in Ontario civic elections for more than 20 years, and also in a 2016 by-election in Whitby-Oshawa.
[src:hydro-one/2018-ontario-election-p02] The original paper ballots marked by voters will be kept for a year along with the digital scans of each ballot by the tabulator.
[src:hydro-one/2018-ontario-election-p02] 38 incumbent Liberal MPPs lost their re-election races, as well as a one Trillium party MPP.
[src:hydro-one/2018-ontario-election-p02] Student Vote elections are mock elections that run parallel to real elections, in which students not of voting age participate.
[src:hydro-one/2018-ontario-election-p02] They are administered by CIVIX Canada, in partnership with Elections Ontario.
[src:hydro-one/2018-ontario-election-p02] Student Vote elections are for educational purposes and do not count towards the actual results.
[src:hydro-one/adam-beck] Beck was born in Baden, Canada West to German immigrants, Jacob Beck and Charlotte Hespeler (sister of William and Jacob Hespeler).
[src:hydro-one/adam-beck] He was the great-great-grandson of Count Károly Andrássy de Csíkszentkirály et Krasznahorka (1723–1795).
[src:hydro-one/adam-beck] He attended school at the Rockwood Academy in Rockwood, Ontario.
[src:hydro-one/adam-beck] As a teenager he worked in his father's foundry, and later established a cigar-box manufacturing company in Galt (now Cambridge, Ontario) with his brother William.
[src:hydro-one/adam-beck] In 1885, he moved the company to London, Ontario, where it quickly flourished and established Beck as a wealthy and influential civic leader.
[src:hydro-one/adam-beck] He was also involved in horse breeding and racing, and at a horse show in 1897 he met Lilian Ottaway of Hamilton daughter of Cuthbert Ottaway and Marion Stinson.
[src:hydro-one/adam-beck] Lilian's mother, by then Marion Crerar, objected to their 21-year age difference – she was 19 and he 40 – as well as Beck's love of horse racing, which they felt would keep him away from home.
[src:hydro-one/adam-beck] Nevertheless, they were married on September 7, 1898.
[src:hydro-one/adam-beck] Beck named their London mansion Headley, after Lilian's parents' home in Surrey, England.
[src:hydro-one/adam-beck] In addition to horse breeding, for which he won numerous prizes, Beck was also associated with tennis and lawn bowling.
[src:hydro-one/adam-beck] Also in 1898, Beck ran for provincial legislature for the first time, but lost.
[src:hydro-one/adam-beck] In 1900, Beck founded the London Health Association, which would later develop into the University and Victoria Hospitals.
[src:hydro-one/adam-beck] In 1902, he was elected mayor of London and a few months later was elected to the Ontario legislature as the Conservative member from the London riding.
[src:hydro-one/adam-beck] He was re-elected mayor in 1903 and 1904 while simultaneously serving as a member of the provincial legislature (which is no longer permitted).
[src:hydro-one/adam-beck] Already a wealthy man, he donated his salary to charity while serving as mayor.
[src:hydro-one/adam-beck] In 1905, he was appointed minister without portfolio in the government of premier Sir James P.
[src:hydro-one/adam-beck] Beck was an early and prominent advocate of publicly owned electricity grids, opposing the privately owned companies who he felt did not adequately serve the needs of the public.
[src:hydro-one/adam-beck] With the slogan "Power at Cost" and in Latin, "*dona naturae pro populo sunt*" ("the gifts of nature are for the public"), he convinced Premier Whitney to create a board of enquiry on the matter, with him as chairman.
[src:hydro-one/adam-beck] The enquiry suggested creating a municipally owned hydroelectric system, funded by the provincial government, and using water from Niagara Falls and other Ontario lakes and rivers.
[src:hydro-one/adam-beck] In 1906 Whitney appointed Beck the first chairman of the Hydro-Electric Power Commission.
[src:hydro-one/adam-beck] He was knighted by King George V in 1914 for his promotion of electricity and development of transmission lines.
[src:hydro-one/adam-beck] In 1915, he tried to introduce a network of interurban railways, known provincially as radials (long-distance trolleys) in Ontario under public ownership, but this plan had to be put on hold during World War I.
[src:hydro-one/adam-beck] In the 1919 post-war election, Beck lost his seat to Hugh Stevenson as the United Farmers of Ontario swept the Conservatives out of power.
[src:hydro-one/adam-beck] Beck continued to push his radial railways proposal after World War I, which pitted him against Premier Ernest Drury, with whom he had an antagonistic relationship.
[src:hydro-one/adam-beck] In 1920, Drury created a Royal Commission, chaired by Robert Franklin Sutherland, which concluded that the popularity of automobiles had rendered Beck's proposal obsolete.
[src:hydro-one/adam-beck] During his time in the provincial legislature Beck remained active in London.
[src:hydro-one/adam-beck] His daughter Marion, born in 1904, suffered from tuberculosis, but with Beck's wealth and influence she had access to the best doctors and medicine.
[src:hydro-one/adam-beck] Realizing that not everyone could afford such care, in 1910 Beck founded a sanitorium, which was very advanced for its time.
[src:hydro-one/adam-beck] The Queen Alexandra Sanitorium, named after Alexandra of Denmark, wife of King Edward VII, was officially opened on April 5 of that year by Governor General Earl Grey.
[src:hydro-one/adam-beck] It was later renamed the Beck Memorial Sanitorium.
[src:hydro-one/adam-beck] Later still it was renamed the Children's Psychiatric Research Institute (CPRI).
[src:hydro-one/adam-beck] Today the building houses the London Child and Parent Resource Institute.
[src:hydro-one/adam-beck] In 1918 Beck also paid fellow Londoner Guy Lombardo to play at Marion's débutante party.
[src:hydro-one/adam-beck] Lilian Beck died of cancer on October 17, 1921.
[src:hydro-one/adam-beck] In 1923 Beck was re-elected to the Ontario legislature, until his own death from anemia in 1925.
[src:hydro-one/adam-beck] Former Prime Minister of Canada Arthur Meighen, Ontario premier George Howard Ferguson, and London mayor George Wenige attended his funeral.
[src:hydro-one/adam-beck] The Queenston Chippawa power station (now Sir Adam Beck Hydroelectric Power Stations), which he helped to create, was renamed after him in 1950.
[src:hydro-one/adam-beck] Also named for him were Sir Adam Beck Collegiate Institute, a public secondary school in London (closed 1982) which is now home to the Thames Valley District School Board headquarters, an elementary school in Upper Beaches, Toronto, Ontario, and a bilingual elementary school in Etobicoke.
[src:hydro-one/adam-beck] Sir Adam Beck Public School was built in his hometown of Baden.
[src:hydro-one/adam-beck] Sir Adam Beck Community Park in Baden is also named in his honour.
[src:hydro-one/adam-beck] In 1990, Headley, the Becks' mansion at Richmond and Sydenham streets, was demolished by Sifton Properties Ltd. and replaced with a condominium replica dubbed the Sir Adam Beck Manor.
[src:hydro-one/adam-beck] In Toronto, there is a statue of Beck (Adam Beck Memorial), sculpted by Emanuel Hahn, on University Avenue at Queen Street West.
[src:hydro-one/adam-beck] It was jointly erected by City of Toronto and the Toronto Hydro-Electric Commission in 1934.
[src:hydro-one/agent-general] Australia's and Canada's federal governments are represented by high commissions, as are all Commonwealth national governments today.
[src:hydro-one/agent-general] In the 18th and 19th centuries, a growing number of British colonies appointed agents in Great Britain and Ireland and occasionally elsewhere in Europe to promote immigration to the colonies.
[src:hydro-one/agent-general] Eventually, agents-general were appointed by some colonies to represent their commercial, legal, and diplomatic interests in Britain and to the British government and Whitehall.
[src:hydro-one/agent-general] They were appointed, and their expenses and salaries provided, by the governments of the colonies they represented.
[src:hydro-one/agent-general] Starting in 1886, Quebec and the federal Canadian government also appointed agents-general to Paris.
[src:hydro-one/agent-general] The first, Hector Fabre, was dispatched by the province of Quebec but was asked by the federal government to represent all of Canada.
[src:hydro-one/agent-general] He and his successor, Philippe Roy, continued to represent both Quebec City and Ottawa in France until 1912 when the federal government asked Roy to resign his Quebec position to avoid conflicts of interest.
[src:hydro-one/agent-general] Canadian provinces have also appointed agents-general (called delegates-general by Quebec beginning in the 1970s) to other countries and major cities.
[src:hydro-one/agent-general] Following a military coup in Nigeria in 1966, the federal system was abolished, and the posts of the agents-general of Nigerian regions in London were subsumed in the Nigerian High Commission.
[src:hydro-one/agent-general] By the 1990s, some Australian state governments regarded the office of their agent-general in London as a costly anachronism, even for promoting tourism and investment, and have since been closed and subsumed into the Australian High Commission.
[src:hydro-one/agent-general] The majority of Australian states continue to have agents-general in London, but operate from Australia House rather than maintain separate premises.
[src:hydro-one/agent-general] Many Canadian provinces similarly are no longer represented by an agent-general, although Quebec continues to have a Government Office in London (*Délégation générale du Québec à Londres*) and in several other cities around the world.
[src:hydro-one/agent-general] Ontario, Alberta, Saskatchewan, and Manitoba have representatives who work out of the Canadian Embassy in Washington, DC.
[src:hydro-one/agent-general] In the United Kingdom, Agents-General of Australia and Canada (and their Staff) are granted the same Diplomatic Privileges and Immunities held under international law by virtue of the *"*Consular Relations Act 1968*", *legislation.gov.uk*, The National Archives, 1978 c.
[src:hydro-one/agent-general] 30*, this privilege is granted under *"*The Commonwealth Countries and Republic of Ireland (Immunities and Privileges) Order 1985*", *legislation.gov.uk*, The National Archives, SI 1985/1983*, these privileges including the right to freedom from arrest and exemption of duties and taxes.
[src:hydro-one/agent-general] Agents-General of other countries are not afforded these privileges.
[src:hydro-one/agent-general] Under international Agents-general have no diplomatic or legal status, privileges or immunities under international but may be granted the privilege of a Diplomatic Passport by some originating countries during their commission.
[src:hydro-one/agent-general] In the Australian colonies and Province of South Australia, prior to each achieving responsible government, each was represented in the United Kingdom by the Colonial Agent.
[src:hydro-one/agent-general] The position was appointed by the British Secretary of State for the Colonies to work within the Office of the Crown Agents for the Colonies; each colony was represented by the same Agent, Edward Barnard, who was not appointed or paid by the colonies.
[src:hydro-one/agent-general] Growing dissatisfaction among colonial governments led, following each colony and province achieving responsible government, to the appointment of individual Agents-General appointed by the relevant colonial government to represent their interest to the Crown and Empire.
[src:hydro-one/agent-general] South Australia was the first Australian colonial government to appoint an Agent-General, with Gregory Seale Walters taking the post in January 1859.
[src:hydro-one/agent-general] Most Australian states continue to maintain Agents-General in London.
[src:hydro-one/agent-general] The Agent-General for South Australia is the official representative of the State of South Australia to the United Kingdom.
[src:hydro-one/agent-general] The position is a quasi-diplomatic representative responsible for representing the State to the Crown and promoting South Australia's trade and economic interests in the United Kingdom and Europe.
[src:hydro-one/agent-general] In 1858, South Australia was the first Australian colonial government to appoint an Agent-General.
[src:hydro-one/agent-general] In 2015, the then Agent-General and advertising executive, Bill Muirhead established the *South Australia Club* in London as a means for South Australian expats and businesses to network with British and European businesses to leverage South Australia's trade and tourism opportunities.
[src:hydro-one/agent-general] Since 2015, the club has grown across many countries around the world; with hopes of expanding further in the future.
[src:hydro-one/agent-general] The New South Wales Office in London was one of several overseas offices established by the colonies of Australia to represent their interests.
[src:hydro-one/agent-general] The London Office was established after the appointment of the first Agent-General on 1 May 1864.
[src:hydro-one/agent-general] In June 1932, the Agent-General's Office was abolished as a cost-cutting measure and was replaced by the New South Wales Government Offices, London, to be headed by an "Official Representative".
[src:hydro-one/agent-general] The title was renamed Agent-General in 1937, but was left vacant from 1939 to 1946 due to the Second World War.
[src:hydro-one/agent-general] From 1972 to 1993, the Agent-General's Office was located in separate premises from Australia House, at the nearby address of 66 The Strand, which was opened by Queen Elizabeth II in May 1972.
[src:hydro-one/agent-general] In October 1992, the position of NSW Agent-General in London was abolished by the Fahey government.
[src:hydro-one/agent-general] This occurred following an expenses scandal by the last Agent-General, Neil Pickard, who had been appointed as a consolation for losing his seat in parliament.
[src:hydro-one/agent-general] Following its abolition, Fahey noted to Parliament: "It was abundantly clear to me, to all Cabinet and to all Government that we no longer needed an agent-general's office in London.
[src:hydro-one/agent-general] That was a throwback to colonial days - to the days when it was important to have garden parties and to participate in ceremonies.
[src:hydro-one/agent-general] The NSW Government of Gladys Berejiklian considered reviving the Agent-General position in late-2019, noting that "We know the post-Brexit environment is going to be very different and NSW can gain a lot of opportunities in business from the UK".
[src:hydro-one/agent-general] The position was revived in 2021, with an expanded remit to additionally cover Europe and Israel.
[src:hydro-one/agent-general] As it was difficult to compete with larger provinces like Ontario and Quebec, the province of Manitoba decided to leave trade promotion to the federal government and accordingly recalled their agent-general in 1965 without appointing a replacement.
[src:hydro-one/agent-general] Quebec uses the title agent-general or delegate-general.
[src:hydro-one/agent-general] In 1936, legislation was passed by the government of Maurice Duplessis closing all Quebec government offices abroad.
[src:hydro-one/agent-general] The government of Adélard Godbout repealed the legislation and opened an office in New York City in 1940.
[src:hydro-one/agent-general] When Duplessis returned to power in 1944, his government retained the New York City office and its agent-general but opened no others.
[src:hydro-one/agent-general] In 1971, the title of agent-general was officially changed to delegate-general although previous title is still often used, particularly for the government's representative to London.
[src:hydro-one/agent-general] As of 2024, the Government of Quebec has 35 offices abroad, including 9 delegates-general.
[src:hydro-one/agent-general] With the granting of responsible self-government to Malta in 1921, a proposal of the government of Lord Strickland to appoint an agent-general to "encourage the migration of Maltese to the Northern Territory and north-west Australia" was presented to the parliament.
[src:hydro-one/agent-general] Strickland, who was Governor of Western Australia (1909–1913) suggested former Colonial Secretary and Agent-General of Western Australia in London, Sir James Connolly.
[src:hydro-one/agent-general] The position was discontinued with the suspension of the constitution in November 1933 and was replaced by a Trade Commissioner, who was in turn replaced by a Commissioner-General in 1947.
[src:hydro-one/agent-general] Prior to the creation of the Union of South Africa in 1910, the four constituent British colonies of southern Africa all sent agents-general to London, coinciding with the establishment of responsible self-government in each colony.
[src:hydro-one/agent-general] The Orange River Colony sent an agent-general from 1908 until the creation of the Union of South Africa in 1910.
[src:hydro-one/agent-general] Brounger was a former director of the Orange Free State Railways.
[src:hydro-one/agent-general] The Transvaal Colony sent an agent-general from the establishment of responsible self-government in 1907 until the creation of the Union of South Africa in 1910.
[src:hydro-one/agent-general] Solomon then served as the first South African High Commissioner in London from 1910 to 1913.
[src:hydro-one/agent-general] The Cape Colony sent separate agents-general until the creation of the Union of South Africa in 1910.
[src:hydro-one/agent-general] The Colony of Natal sent separate agents-general until the creation of the Union of South Africa in 1910.
[src:hydro-one/agent-general] After 1905 the position of Agent-General was replaced by that of High Commissioner, with the final Agent-General becoming the first High Commissioner.
[src:hydro-one/agnico-eagle] In 1953, five struggling mining companies joined to become Cobalt Consolidated Mining, which would last until 1957, when the company changed its name to Agnico Mines.
[src:hydro-one/agnico-eagle] "Agnico" is derived from the periodic table of elements using the symbols for silver (Ag), nickel (Ni) and cobalt (Co).
[src:hydro-one/agnico-eagle] In 1963, Paul Penna became the president of Agnico Mines, and he eventually oversaw the merger of Agnico Mines with Eagle Mines Ltd, a successful gold exploration company, enabling the development of Eagle's Joutel mining complex in northern Quebec.
[src:hydro-one/agnico-eagle] The newly formed company became Agnico Eagle Mines Limited.
[src:hydro-one/agnico-eagle] In 1974, the Joutel mine went into production and would eventually produce approximately 1.1 million ounces of gold until its closure in 1993.
[src:hydro-one/agnico-eagle] During this period, Agnico Eagle also acquired the property and assets of Dumagami Mines Limited in north-western Quebec, which had recently gone into production a year earlier in 1988.
[src:hydro-one/agnico-eagle] The Dumagami mine would eventually be renamed the LaRonde mine, which is now considered the flagship mining operation for Agnico Eagle, and one of the largest gold deposits in Canada.
[src:hydro-one/agnico-eagle] With LaRonde producing steadily, Agnico Eagle acquired more assets over the following years.
[src:hydro-one/agnico-eagle] In 1993, they completed the purchase of the Goldex mine, becoming the 100% owner of the largest unexploited gold deposit in Quebec.
[src:hydro-one/agnico-eagle] As a result of these purchases, the following years would see Agnico Eagle grow from a single-operation gold producer (LaRonde) to a much larger company consisting of 6 mines in total, with Goldex going into production in 2008, Kittila, Lapa and Pinos Altos in 2009, and Meadowbank in 2010.
[src:hydro-one/agnico-eagle] In 2010, Agnico Eagle completed the purchase of the Meliadine property, located southeast of Meadowbank near Rankin Inlet, Nunavut.
[src:hydro-one/agnico-eagle] In 2011, the company also announced a $70 million (CAD) investment in Rubicon Minerals, representing a 9.2% ownership stake and access to the Phoenix gold project located in the heart of Red Lake, Ontario.
[src:hydro-one/agnico-eagle] In 2016, Agnico Eagle was ranked as the 14th best of 92 oil, gas, and mining companies on indigenous rights in Arctic resource extraction.
[src:hydro-one/agnico-eagle] In 2018, CEO Sean Boyd received *The Northern Miner'*s "Mining Person of the Year Award" at the annual Pacific Mine Forum (PMF).
[src:hydro-one/agnico-eagle] In the 2021 Arctic Environmental Responsibility Index (AERI) Agnico Eagle Mines Limited was ranked no.
[src:hydro-one/agnico-eagle] 35 among 120 oil, gas, and mining companies involved in resource extraction north of the Arctic Circle.
[src:hydro-one/agnico-eagle] In 2021, a $13.5 billion merger between Kirkland Lake Gold and Agnico consolidated the largest gold mines in Canada's Abitibi gold belt.
[src:hydro-one/agnico-eagle] In 2025, Agnico Eagle Mines Limited completed the acquisition of 100% of O3 Mining Inc. for CAD $1.67 per share in cash, adding the Marban deposit in Québec to its development pipeline.
[src:hydro-one/agnico-eagle] The company reported record financial results, including third-quarter net income of US$1.055 billion (US$2.10 per share) and adjusted net income of US$1.085 billion (US$2.16 per share), supported by gold production of 866,936 ounces at an average realized price of US$3,476 per ounce.
[src:hydro-one/agnico-eagle] Agnico Eagle transitioned from a net debt position to net cash of US$2.16 billion, repaid US$550 million in debt, and returned US$300 million to shareholders through dividends and buybacks.
[src:hydro-one/agnico-eagle] The company advanced several growth projects, including the Odyssey underground expansion at Canadian Malartic, development of an exploration ramp at Detour Lake, and resource expansion drilling at Hope Bay and Upper Beaver, where shaft construction was scheduled for late 2025.
[src:hydro-one/agnico-eagle] A feasibility study for the San Nicolás copper-zinc project in Mexico was expected by year-end.
[src:hydro-one/agnico-eagle] In April 2025, Agnico Eagle published its 16th Sustainability Report, reaffirming its commitment to net-zero Scope 1 and 2 emissions by 2050, with an interim target of 30% reduction by 2030.
[src:hydro-one/agnico-eagle] The company increased investment in energy efficiency and low-carbon technologies and expanded community engagement and Indigenous partnerships.
[src:hydro-one/agnico-eagle] The LaRonde mine, formerly Dumagami Mine, is located alongside the Trans-Canada highway in the Abitibi-Témiscamingue region between Rouyn-Noranda and Val-d'or, Quebec.
[src:hydro-one/agnico-eagle] LaRonde's Penna shaft, also known as shaft 3, is believed to be the deepest single lift shaft in the Western Hemisphere, descending more than three kilometres (or 9800 ft) below the surface.
[src:hydro-one/agnico-eagle] It is estimated to have the longest potential lifespan of Agnico Eagle's six operating mines, estimated to be approximately 35 years once completed, from 1988 to 2023.
[src:hydro-one/agnico-eagle] The lifespan is now expected to run until 2032.
[src:hydro-one/agnico-eagle] The operation currently mines gold, zinc, copper and silver ores and employs 1,042 workers.
[src:hydro-one/agnico-eagle] The mine was renamed to the LaRonde Mine by company founder Paul Penna, to honour its first project manager, mining engineer Donald J.
[src:hydro-one/agnico-eagle] Employing 213 people, with an estimated mine life of 10 years (2008–2018); Goldex is an underground mine located just outside Val-d'Or, Quebec, Canada.
[src:hydro-one/agnico-eagle] Goldex is unique due to its partnership with the Quebec government in the restoration of the nearby abandoned Manitou mine tailings site.
[src:hydro-one/agnico-eagle] Not only do the Goldex tailings neutralize and help rehabilitate the site, but the system also eliminates the need for a tailings pond at the Goldex site itself.
[src:hydro-one/agnico-eagle] The mine is expected to run until 2032 and currently produces roughly 134,000 oz of gold per year.
[src:hydro-one/agnico-eagle] Lapa, located about 11 km away from the LaRonde mine (see above), in the Rivière-Héva municipality of the Abitibi region in Quebec, Canada, is one of Agnico Eagle's smaller operations employing 192 people, with a 6-year mine life expectancy (2009–2015).
[src:hydro-one/agnico-eagle] The main headframe that is used at the Lapa mine was constructed almost entirely from a pre-existing headframe at LaRonde.
[src:hydro-one/agnico-eagle] The original headframe was dismantled, sand blasted and painted before it was installed at Lapa.
[src:hydro-one/agnico-eagle] Although Lapa may be a smaller operation in comparison to our other mines, it is one of Agnico Eagle's highest-grade mines, with reserve grades twice as rich as the company average.
[src:hydro-one/agnico-eagle] In the Lapland region of Northern Finland, Agnico Eagle's Kittilä operation has a life expectancy of 23 years (2009–2032).
[src:hydro-one/agnico-eagle] With 375 employees, this open pit and underground mine is one of the largest known gold deposits in all of Europe, containing almost 4.9 million ounces of gold in reserves.
[src:hydro-one/agnico-eagle] Aggressive exploration is also currently underway; with the Kittilä mine serving notice that gold-mining is again a booming industry in northern Finland.
[src:hydro-one/agnico-eagle] Agnico Eagle's largest employer, with 972 employees, is the Pinos Altos mine located in the state of Chihuahua, in northern Mexico.
[src:hydro-one/agnico-eagle] Pinos Altos began operation in 2009 and is expected to continue until 2026, resulting in an estimated 17 years of production.
[src:hydro-one/agnico-eagle] The open-pit and underground mining operation is in the mountainous Sierra Madre gold and silver belt of northern Mexico.
[src:hydro-one/agnico-eagle] La India is an open pit mine is located approximately 200 km east of Hermosillo in Sonora, Mexico.
[src:hydro-one/agnico-eagle] It began production in February 2014 and has a mine life expectancy of 6 years.
[src:hydro-one/agnico-eagle] Meadowbank is an open-pit mine in the Kivalliq Region of Nunavut with an 8-year life expectancy (2010 – 2017).
[src:hydro-one/agnico-eagle] Meadowbank is one of Agnico Eagle's most recent mine to begin operation, and has about 650 employees.
[src:hydro-one/agnico-eagle] In 2010 the first gold brick was poured at Meadowbank, which was also the first ever gold brick to be poured in the history of Nunavut.
[src:hydro-one/agnico-eagle] Meadowbank is also Agnico Eagle's largest producer, estimated to produce 430,000 ounces of gold in 2014.
[src:hydro-one/agnico-eagle] The open-pit Detour Lake operation is the largest gold producing mine in Canada with the country's largest gold mineral reserves.
[src:hydro-one/agnico-eagle] Located within the northernmost Abitibi Greenstone Belt, the mine was originally owned by Placer Dome and operated primarily as an underground mine from 1987 to 1990.
[src:hydro-one/agnico-eagle] Production resumed in 2013 as an open-pit mine under the ownership of Detour Gold Corporation.
[src:hydro-one/agnico-eagle] Agnico Eagle acquired its interest in the Detour Lake mine on February 8, 2022.
[src:hydro-one/agnico-eagle] With exploration beginning in 1931 and first production beginning in 1933, Macassa remains one of the world's highest-grade gold mines.
[src:hydro-one/agnico-eagle] The #4 Shaft production hoist, commissioned in 2023, has started a new chapter in the life of the Macassa mine, increasing production, improving working conditions, lowering unit costs and increasing exploration capacity.
[src:hydro-one/agnico-eagle] The 2011 exploration program is expected to include more than 410 km of planned drilling to expand resources and convert our large gold resource to reserves.
[src:hydro-one/agnico-eagle] In December 2016 Agnico invested CA$4.5 million into Canadian junior mining company Cartier Resources to conduct exploration on the Chimo, Benoist, Wilson, Fenton and Cadillac Extension projects in Quebec.
[src:hydro-one/agnico-eagle] Agnico-Eagle Mines Group reported Total CO2e emissions (Direct + Indirect) for 31 December 2020 at 578 Kt (+57/+11% y-o-y).
[src:hydro-one/agnico-eagle] The growth accelerated compared to the long-term upward trend (CAGR of +7.6% since 4Q'16).
[src:hydro-one/agnico-eagle] In 2025, Agnico Eagle faced regulatory and community challenges in Nunavut.
[src:hydro-one/agnico-eagle] A federal investigation found violations of caribou protection measures at the Whale Tail and Meadowbank mines, including failure to secure Free, Prior, and Informed Consent (FPIC) from Indigenous stakeholders.
[src:hydro-one/agnico-eagle] The company also withdrew its proposal to extend the Meliadine mine after the Nunavut Impact Review Board recommended against it due to environmental concerns, particularly impacts on the Qamanirjuaq caribou herd.
[src:hydro-one/agricultural-research-institute-of-ontario] Established in 1962 as the **Agricultural Research Institute of Ontario** (*Institut de recherche agricole de l'Ontario*), the agency amanages agricultural research priorities and infrastructure through partnerships with government, industry, and academic institutions.
[src:hydro-one/agricultural-research-institute-of-ontario] It was renamed in 2024 following amendments to the *Agricultural Research Institute of Ontario Act* that expanded its mandate to emphasize innovation, commercialization, and strategic collaboration.
[src:hydro-one/agricultural-research-institute-of-ontario] ARIO is headquartered in Guelph, Ontario, and maintains a longstanding partnership with the University of Guelph through the *Ontario Agri-Food Innovation Alliance*.
[src:hydro-one/alcohol-and-gaming-commission-of-ontario] The **Alcohol and Gaming Commission of Ontario** (**AGCO**) is a Crown regulatory agency responsible for the regulation of the alcohol, gaming, horse racing, and cannabis retail sectors in the Canadian province of Ontario.
[src:hydro-one/alcohol-and-gaming-commission-of-ontario] The AGCO reports to the Attorney General of Ontario.
[src:hydro-one/alcohol-and-gaming-commission-of-ontario] The AGCO was established on February 23, 1998, by the Government of Ontario under the *Alcohol and Gaming Regulation and Public Protection Act* of 1996.
[src:hydro-one/alcohol-and-gaming-commission-of-ontario] This Act transferred responsibility for the *Liquor Licence Act* and the *Gaming Control Act* to the newly formed AGCO.
[src:hydro-one/alcohol-and-gaming-commission-of-ontario] As a result, the Government of Ontario subsequently passed legislation dissolving the Liquor Licence Board of Ontario, the Racing Commission of Ontario, and the Gaming Control Commission.
[src:hydro-one/alcohol-and-gaming-commission-of-ontario] On April 1, 2016, the AGCO assumed responsibility for regulating horse racing under the *Horse Racing Licence Act, 2015*.
[src:hydro-one/alcohol-and-gaming-commission-of-ontario] With the legalization of cannabis in Canada, the AGCO assumed responsibility for regulating private cannabis retail stores under the Cannabis Licence Act, 2018 on October 17, 2018.
[src:hydro-one/alectra-utilities] When it was founded, Alectra was described as the second largest municipally owned electricity utility in North America after the Los Angeles Department of Water and Power.
[src:hydro-one/alectra-utilities] As of January 2019 it is the largest municipally owned electricity utility in Canada, by number of customers served.
[src:hydro-one/alectra-utilities] Alectra was formed on January 31, 2017 by the merger of the municipally owned utilities Enersource (servicing Mississauga), Horizon Utilities (servicing Hamilton and St.
[src:hydro-one/alectra-utilities] Catharines), and PowerStream (servicing multiple municipalities in York Region and Simcoe County, including the city of Barrie).
[src:hydro-one/alectra-utilities] The initial formation of the company was completed with the acquisition of Hydro One Brampton from the provincial government's Hydro One on February 28, 2017.
[src:hydro-one/alectra-utilities] Guelph Hydro (serving Guelph and Rockwood) merged into Alectra on January 1, 2019.
[src:hydro-one/alectra-utilities] Following its formation, Alectra continued to hold the 50% ownership stake formerly held by PowerStream in Collus PowerStream (which services Collingwood and surrounding area) until 2017.
[src:hydro-one/alectra-utilities] Alectra announced on November 9, 2017 that it was selling its ownership stake in Collus PowerStream back to the Town of Collingwood, with the Town announcing that it was selling Collus PowerStream to EPCOR Utilities.
[src:hydro-one/alectra-utilities] On January 5, 2021, Alectra acquired power restoration company Holland Power Services based in Maugerville, New Brunswick.
[src:hydro-one/alectra-utilities] Holland Power Services operates throughout the east coast of Canada and the United States and has 5 locations: 1 in New Brunswick (headquarters), 2 in Ontario, 1 in Quebec, and 1 in Maine, USA.
[src:hydro-one/alectra-utilities] On June 10, 2024, Alectra announced their acquisition of another power restoration company, Gagnon Line Construction, based in Grand Falls/Grand Sault, New Brunswick.
[src:hydro-one/alectra-utilities] Gagnon Line Construction has two locations: 1 in New Brunswick, and 1 in Quebec.
[src:hydro-one/alectra-utilities] The acquisition of both Holland Power Services and Gagnon Line Construction makes Alectra the largest storm restoration company in Eastern Canada.
[src:hydro-one/alectra-utilities] The company is governed by a 14-member board of directors representing the municipalities and other shareholders which owned its predecessor companies.
[src:hydro-one/alectra-utilities] Municipal representatives make up 13 of those directors, consisting of: 4 directors from Mississauga, 3 from Vaughan, 2 from Hamilton, 2 from Markham, 1 from Barrie, 1 from St.
[src:hydro-one/alectra-utilities] Employees of Alectra's predecessor companies had previously been represented by the Power Workers' Union, the International Brotherhood of Electrical Workers, and Unifor.
[src:hydro-one/alectra-utilities] Following a vote on June 28, 2017 the majority of unionized employees of Alectra and its subsidiaries agreed to be represented solely by the Power Workers' Union.
[src:hydro-one/hydro-one] Hydro One was established at this time as a corporation under the *Business Corporations Act* with the Government of Ontario as sole shareholder.
[src:hydro-one/hydro-one] Following its initial public offering on the Toronto Stock Exchange in 2015, the Government of Ontario began selling shares to the public with a final goal of 60% of the company being held by private investors.
[src:hydro-one/hydro-one] A report released on December 2, 2015, by the Auditor General of Ontario raised concern with the sale, indicating that power outages are increasing and that Hydro One's equipment is aging and "at very high risk of failing".
[src:hydro-one/hydro-one] The estimated cost of necessary repairs was $4.472 billion.
[src:hydro-one/hydro-one] Hydro One is a holding company with four subsidiaries, the largest being Hydro One Networks.
[src:hydro-one/hydro-one] It operates 98% of the high voltage transmission grid throughout Ontario, and serves 1.4 million customers primarily in rural areas across the province in its capacity as Ontario's largest distribution utility.
[src:hydro-one/hydro-one] Hydro One has interconnections with Manitoba Hydro, Hydro-Québec, Minnesota Power, DTE Energy/ITC, National Grid (the former Niagara Mohawk Power) and the New York Power Authority.
[src:hydro-one/hydro-one] Hydro One works with the transmission and distribution network by connecting generating facilities operated by Ontario Power Generation, Bruce Power, and a number of other privately owned companies, to it.
[src:hydro-one/hydro-one] The generators deliver the electricity they generate at hydroelectric, natural gas, wind, solar and nuclear facilities to businesses and people across Ontario.
[src:hydro-one/hydro-one] The generators have different responsibilities than Hydro One.
[src:hydro-one/hydro-one] The power from generators connected to Hydro One's high voltage system is transformed to more than 50 kV (50,000 volts).
[src:hydro-one/hydro-one] The transmission-connected generators are registered with the Independent Electricity System Operator (IESO).
[src:hydro-one/hydro-one] Transmission lines, strung between metal towers or concrete poles, are not as plentiful as their distribution lines, which are most commonly strung between wooden poles.
[src:hydro-one/hydro-one] The distribution system is connected to Hydro One's generating facilities.
[src:hydro-one/hydro-one] It delivers the electricity generated at hydroelectric, wind and other facilities to businesses and people across Ontario.
[src:hydro-one/hydro-one] These distribution facilities work at voltages of 50 kV or less.
[src:hydro-one/hydro-one] More than 75% of the applications to connect small generators are in Hydro One's rural service territory along the company's distribution system.
[src:hydro-one/hydro-one] While Hydro One has connected thousands of small projects to the grid it is approaching their technical limits of the wires and equipment in some rural locations.
[src:hydro-one/hydro-one] In these areas there are two issues that limit the number of projects that Hydro One can safely connect without putting the grid in jeopardy.
[src:hydro-one/hydro-one] The first issue is the physical limits of the power lines and the second is a phenomenon called 'islanding'.
[src:hydro-one/hydro-one] In larger areas that are densely populated, Hydro One's wires are thicker and designed to deliver larger amounts of electricity.
[src:hydro-one/hydro-one] In rural areas, Hydro One's distribution wires are smaller, thinner and deliver a smaller amount of electricity because they were designed to serve a much smaller number of customers than in large urban centers.
[src:hydro-one/hydro-one] These thinner lines deliver electricity safely and reliably to rural customers and are able to support the connection of small generation projects spread across the line, but these lines become over loaded when more electricity is fed back to the grid than the line was built to deliver.
[src:hydro-one/hydro-one] In some areas where the program is extremely popular, many generators want to connect to the same thin line but the line is not able to support the transfer of so much electricity.
[src:hydro-one/hydro-one] Hydro One's distribution system knows how to protect itself under certain conditions.
[src:hydro-one/hydro-one] For instance, during a storm if a tree falls on a line, the system shuts itself down, similar to a circuit breaker.
[src:hydro-one/hydro-one] This protects the company's customers and employees from accidentally coming into contact with a live electrical line; it also protects appliances like televisions from uncontrolled surges and drops in voltage.
[src:hydro-one/hydro-one] In addition, when there is a fault, the line must be dead.
[src:hydro-one/hydro-one] Also when solar panels are attached to such lines, they must also be shut down when there is a fault on the line.
[src:hydro-one/hydro-one] If they are not shut down, electricity keeps flowing from the solar panels to all points between the panels.
[src:hydro-one/hydro-one] This can create an unsafe condition called islanding, which can put at risk customers, employees, and the equipment drawing power from that line.
[src:hydro-one/hydro-one] Hydro One prevents islanding by limiting the amount of generation that the company connects in one area; this ensures that the electrical load is greater than generation at all times.
[src:hydro-one/hydro-one] Ontario has moved to smart meters, which could support even more solutions to these problems.
[src:hydro-one/hydro-one] By using the company's existing network and working with customers, Hydro One is exploring new ways to deliver the cleaner electricity which Ontarians are helping to generate.
[src:hydro-one/hydro-one] The first chairman was Adam Beck, minister without portfolio in the provincial government of Sir James P.
[src:hydro-one/hydro-one] Beck had been an advocate for a publicly owned electricity grid.
[src:hydro-one/hydro-one] The commission's initial responsibility was to build transmission lines in order to supply municipal utilities with power.
[src:hydro-one/hydro-one] The power that was being transferred by HEPC was already being generated at Niagara Falls by private companies.
[src:hydro-one/hydro-one] Also during 1906, the company appointed Adam Beck as chairman.
[src:hydro-one/hydro-one] A year later, Beck and his colleague William Peyton Hubbard fought for the public ownership of the company.
[src:hydro-one/hydro-one] Later in 1908, HEPC purchased power from Niagara Falls and sought to transmit this power over its own lines, which at the time, had not been established.
[src:hydro-one/hydro-one] The company continued its steady growth for the next few years. and by 1914 HEPC built its first owned power generating station located on the Severn River.
[src:hydro-one/hydro-one] In the early 1920s, HEPC expanded further and became an electricity distributor itself.
[src:hydro-one/hydro-one] The company now transmitted to rural areas in addition to municipal utilities.
[src:hydro-one/hydro-one] In 1922 the company's first unit of the Chippawa hydroelectric development on the Niagara River began service.
[src:hydro-one/hydro-one] Upon the unit's completion in 1925, it was the largest generating station in the world.
[src:hydro-one/hydro-one] HEPC bought the generation and transmission assets of the Electrical Development Corporation, which was the last remaining private power company.
[src:hydro-one/hydro-one] In 1926, HEPC entered into a long-term contract with Gatineau Power Company, located in Quebec.
[src:hydro-one/hydro-one] These contracts were needed to accommodate a growing demand for power and electricity.
[src:hydro-one/hydro-one] However, these same contracts were to become a source of controversy during the Great Depression when there was an overcapacity in the system.
[src:hydro-one/hydro-one] Lawrence and Ottawa rivers was stalled by jurisdictional complications.
[src:hydro-one/hydro-one] The development of the rivers would have allowed access to a preferred source of power.
[src:hydro-one/hydro-one] In 1939 the Quebec contracts were reinstated and the development of the rivers were continued.
[src:hydro-one/hydro-one] In the late 1940s and early 1950s HEPC took a great leap forward with development of hydro-electric potential along the St.
[src:hydro-one/hydro-one] During the mid-1950s HEPC joined all its power stations and transmission systems into one network in order to become more efficient and flexible.
[src:hydro-one/hydro-one] Also during the 1950s, hydro-electric development was supplemented by the construction of thermal coal-fired power stations in Toronto.
[src:hydro-one/hydro-one] And by the end of the 1950s HEPC began construction of Canada's first extra-high voltage (500,000-volt) transmission lines.
[src:hydro-one/hydro-one] This brought power from northern Ontario to demand in southern Ontario.
[src:hydro-one/hydro-one] However, these transmission lines would only come into service in 1967.
[src:hydro-one/hydro-one] And by the start of the 1970s all of Ontario's power systems had merged, creating a province-wide grid.
[src:hydro-one/hydro-one] In 1974, the *Power Corporation Act* reorganized the system as a crown corporation called "Ontario Hydro", the name by which it was most usually known.
[src:hydro-one/hydro-one] In 1998, the Progressive Conservative Party (PC) government of Mike Harris passed the *Energy Competition Act* which authorized the establishment of a market in electricity.
[src:hydro-one/hydro-one] The two commercial companies, Ontario Power Generation and Hydro One, were intended to operate as private businesses rather than as crown corporations.
[src:hydro-one/hydro-one] By 2001, Hydro One had acquired 88 municipal utilities.
[src:hydro-one/hydro-one] In December 2001 the provincial government announced its intention to sell Hydro One under an initial public offering (IPO), however by April 2002 various groups in opposition to the plan challenged the government in the Ontario Superior Court of Justice, forcing a halt to the IPO.
[src:hydro-one/hydro-one] In 2002, an electricity market began operating.
[src:hydro-one/hydro-one] However, critics questioned, among other things, whether the market was truly competitive or could ever become competitive, given that an electricity grid is not a private good.
[src:hydro-one/hydro-one] Public dismay at an increase in prices led the government of Harris's successor, Ernie Eves, to freeze electricity prices for residential and small business consumers.
[src:hydro-one/hydro-one] This freeze was maintained after the Liberal Party of Dalton McGuinty replaced the PC government in 2003.
[src:hydro-one/hydro-one] The freeze was removed and prices were raised in April 2004, and have been increased again subsequently.
[src:hydro-one/hydro-one] In 2017, Hydro One agreed to acquire U.S. energy company Avista for CA$6.7 billion in cash.
[src:hydro-one/hydro-one] In 2018, the annual CA$6.2 million compensation paid to CEO Mayo Schmidt became a campaign issue in the 2018 Ontario election.
[src:hydro-one/hydro-one] Progressive Conservative Party leader Doug Ford promised to remove Schmidt if elected, although it was speculated that it would cost CA$10.7 million in severance payments under a clause of "change of control" in Schmidt's contract, which shareholders had approved in May.
[src:hydro-one/hydro-one] The PCs won the election and in July 2018, the newly elected government convinced CEO Mayo Schmidt to retire immediately.
[src:hydro-one/hydro-one] News reports indicated that Schmidt would receive a payment of CA$400,000 in lieu of continuing benefits and would also be entitled to receive incentive bonuses for previous years' achievements, Hydro One stock with a value of approximately CA$9 million.
[src:hydro-one/hydro-one] His annual pension was estimated as exceeding CA$160,000.
[src:hydro-one/hydro-one] The government and other major shareholders in Hydro One then began the process of appointing an entirely new board of directors after accepting the resignation of all previous members.
[src:hydro-one/hydro-one] The new Board is searching for a chief executive to replace Schmidt.
[src:hydro-one/hydro-one] In the interim, CFO Paul Dobson is serving as acting CEO.
[src:hydro-one/hydro-one] In December 2018 the Washington Utilities and Transportation Commission blocked the purchase of Avista, citing concerns about the independence of Hydro One from the provincial government.
[src:hydro-one/hydro-one] Hydro One paid Avista a $103 million termination fee.
[src:hydro-one/hydro-one] In March 2025, Hydro One Networks announced that it completed the acquisition of a 48% interest in the East-West Tie Limited Partnership, which owns the East-West Tie line, a 450-kilometre line between Wawa and Thunder Bay, for CAD 261 million.
[src:hydro-one/hydro-one] Between 1998 and 2000, Hydro One acquired 88 municipal electrical utilities.
[src:hydro-one/hydro-one] Many local/municipal distribution companies were also consolidated during this time.
[src:hydro-one/hydro-one] In May 2002, the provincial government launched an open electricity market, although generating and distribution remained under control of the government.
[src:hydro-one/hydro-one] From 2000 to 2017, Hydro One directly owned the distribution utility for the city of Brampton.
[src:hydro-one/hydro-one] This subsidiary operated separately from the main Hydro One corporation and operated only in the city of Brampton.
[src:hydro-one/hydro-one] Hydro One Brampton was acquired by Alectra Utilities on February 28, 2017.
[src:hydro-one/hydro-one] In August 2014, Hydro One acquired the assets and customers of Norfolk Power.
[src:hydro-one/hydro-one] On October 29, 2015, Premier Kathleen Wynne confirmed rumours that the province planned to sell 60% of Hydro One ("broadening of ownership"), essentially completing the plan proposed by the PC government decades before.
[src:hydro-one/hydro-one] Some of the proceeds from the sale of shares would be used to begin financing of Premier Wynne's 10-year plan for public transit and infrastructure projects in addition to reducing the provincial deficit.
[src:hydro-one/hydro-one] The plan was criticized by many, including Stephen LeClair, the new financial accountability officer for Ontario.
[src:hydro-one/hydro-one] LeClair warned that the sale of an entity that generated a $750 million profit in 2014 would lead to a long term negative financial impact for the province.
[src:hydro-one/hydro-one] The sale will certainly provide short term benefits, generating an estimated total of $9 billion at a time when the provincial government is "desperate for money" (according to *The Globe and Mail*), with one of the largest subsovereign debts in the world.
[src:hydro-one/hydro-one] The estimated revenue will not all be a windfall for the provincial coffers however, since roughly $5 billion is earmarked to pay down Hydro One's $8.5 billion debt.
[src:hydro-one/hydro-one] The balance of the revenue from the Hydro One sale would help meet the targets laid out by the provincial Liberal government in its April 2015 budget.
[src:hydro-one/hydro-one] Although the budget announced some austerity measures, there was no indication of any new revenue sources.
[src:hydro-one/hydro-one] Even so, the plan was to reduce the Province's estimated budget deficit by $2.5 billion to $8.5 billion in the 2015–16 fiscal year, then to $4.8 billion in 2016–17 and to have a balanced budget by 2017–18, according to Finance Minister Charles Sousa.
[src:hydro-one/hydro-one] On November 5, 2015, the province began the first phase of the process, with an initial public offering (IPO) of 81.1 million shares (equivalent to 13.6% of Hydro One) on the Toronto Stock Exchange.
[src:hydro-one/hydro-one] It was the largest IPO in Canada since 2000.
[src:hydro-one/hydro-one] The estimated proceeds from this IPO were expected to total $1.83 billion.
[src:hydro-one/hydro-one] This was the first step in the long-term goal of gradually selling 60% of the utility.
[src:hydro-one/hydro-one] Three more offerings, roughly the same size, followed in 2016 and 2017.
[src:hydro-one/hydro-one] Finance Minister Sousa stated on November 4, 2015, that the Hydro One IPO was already "oversubscribed" at that time, with more advance orders than the shares that would be available.
[src:hydro-one/hydro-one] On November 5, 2015, the stock closed at $21.62, up 5.46% or $1.12 from the IPO price of $20.50, with more than 18 million shares sold.
[src:hydro-one/hydro-one] Although this is not necessarily indicative of a rosy future for the share price, Sousa was optimistic.
[src:hydro-one/hydro-one] Some consumer advocacy groups and some analysts raised red flags, concerned with the risk of increasing electricity costs under a privatized Hydro One.
[src:hydro-one/hydro-one] "Internal polling done for the Wynne government — released under Access to Information — found that 73 per cent of Ontarians oppose the government's plans to privatize Hydro One, the key transmission arm of the original public utility," noted Linda McQuaig in a 2016 *Toronto Star* opinion article.
[src:hydro-one/hydro-one] On the other hand, Brady Yauch, executive director of the Consumer Policy Institute discussed the potential benefits in an opinion piece in the *Financial Post*, including "lower rates for ratepayers".
[src:hydro-one/hydro-one] His premise is based on the potential increase in productivity of Hydro One under private control, "something that the government has failed to do adequately", bringing high salaries into line, and reducing pension liabilities in future, with employees contributing higher amounts to their pensions.
[src:hydro-one/hydro-one] "Given the government's performance over the last 15 years, it calls for hopeful optimism ...", said Yauch.
[src:hydro-one/hydro-one] A secondary offering of 72.4 million Hydro One shares, equivalent to 14.5%, in April 2016 generated $1.7 billion in revenue for the provincial government.
[src:hydro-one/hydro-one] Crown corporation Ontario Power Generation purchased 9 million of the shares, giving it a 1.5% stake in Hydro One.
[src:hydro-one/hydro-one] In May 2017, the Ontario government completed the third and final sale of Hydro One shares worth $2.8 billion.
[src:hydro-one/hydro-one] After the offering, Ontario held 48.9% of Hydro One's common shares: 47.4% directly held by the government, and 1.5% held by Ontario Power Generation.
[src:hydro-one/hydro-one] The Province of Ontario is a shareholder of Hydro One with approximately 47.2% ownership at September 30, 2021.
[src:hydro-one/hydro-one] As part of the partial privatization of Hydro One, the provincial government announced it would sell up to 15 million shares (2.5%) to the indigenous and Métis nations of Ontario for "their collective benefit".
[src:hydro-one/hydro-one] In January 2018 the Ontario government announced it had sold over 14 million shares of Hydro One to OFN Power Holdings, a partnership controlled by 129 First Nations around the province.
[src:hydro-one/hydro-one] The shares represented 2.4% of outstanding common shares, reducing the government's stake in the company to approximately 47.4%.
